
@startuml

' Employees
class Employee {
  - name: String
  - socialSecurityNumber: String
}

' Creative Employees
class CreativeEmployee <|-- Employee

' Directors
class Director {
  - hasOscar: Boolean
  - assistantName: String
}

' Actors
class Actor {
  - education: String
  - hasOscar: Boolean
}

' Technicians
class Technician {
  - fieldOfActivity: String
}

' Film Set
class FilmSet {
  - location: String
  - films: List<Film>
}

' Film
class Film {
  - title: String
  - yearOfRelease: int
  - genre: String
  - filmSets: List<FilmSet>
  - screenplay: Screenplay
}

' Screenwriter
class Screenwriter {
  - name: String
  - mostSuccessfulFilm: String
}

' Screenplay
class Screenplay {
  - title: String
  - version: int
  - date: Date
  - numberOfScenes: int
  - plot: String
  - basis: String
  - novel: Novel
}

' Novel
class Novel {
  - title: String
  - author: String
}

' Relationships
CreativeEmployee <|-- Director
CreativeEmployee <|-- Actor
Employee <|-- Technician

Film "1" -- "0..*" FilmSet : uses
Film "1" -- "1" Screenplay : based on
Screenplay "1" -- "1" Novel : based on (optional)
Screenwriter "1" -- "1" Screenplay : writes

@enduml

### Notes:
- The `CreativeEmployee` is a subclass of `Employee`, which includes both `Director` and `Actor`.
- `Technician` is also an `Employee`, but with different attributes.
- A `Film` can be associated with multiple `FilmSet`s and one `Screenplay`.
- A `Screenplay` is written by exactly one `Screenwriter` and may be based on a `Novel`.
- The `FilmSet` can be used for multiple `Films`.

